Actually 40 Kf1 holds the most chances and black must play accurately for the win: 40 ... Rf2+ 41 Kg1 Rxh7.  The best white can hope for is to win black's "a" pawn but in the meantime white's "c" pawns will fall if not his "f" pawn.
the win is no problem.  black is ready to advance his "a" pawn and follow up with an ... e2 as needed to force a pawn promotion.  white is helpless to prevent this.

As White I've always preferred the closed and semi-closed openings. Closed openings start with 1. d4 d5. Semi-closed ones start with 1.d4 and black responds with some move other than 1. ... d5. The Open Game is 1.e4 e5 a Semi-Open Game (such as this one we played) is 1.e4 where black makes moves other than 1...e5. Flank openings 1.c4 1.Nf3 1.f4 can easily transpose into closed or semi-closed (or sometimes open or semi-open).
***********************************************************************
So I like closed and semi-closed. You on the other hand are playing for the Open Game or Semi-Open Game. Which one depends on my response.
***********************************************************************

None of these categories are better or worse for Black or White. They are more only a matter of preference.

So when my opponent has White and plays 1.e4 I prefer the Semi-Open game. I play the French Defense (1...e6) the Pirc Defense (pronounced "peerts" not "perk" 1...d6) or Alekhine's Defense (1...Nf6).

***********************************************************************

You should study one opening at a time for at least a year and get really good at it. Then move on to study another opening. Currently for this 12 month period (starting early July) I am studying through the French so I only respond to 1.e4 with 1...e6.

***********************************************************************

Key Principle: Study one opening at a time for at least a year until you know it in and out. This does not mean you don't continue to learn other openings but that your primary focus is on only one.

So Chase one reason I like the openings I mentioned (the French Defense the Pirc Defense and Alekhine's Defense) is that in each one Black willingly allows White to establish an imposing pawn center with intention of attacking and destroying that center! So it's an intense debate between the 2 sides a debate won not with words but in tactical chess moves.

***********************************************************************

White says "My solid pawn center will restrict your pieces giving me a superior position!" Black says "Your pawns are weak! I'll use my pawns to destroy your weak pawn center! I will undermine those overly advanced pawns and trade them off and gain a free open position!" 

***********************************************************************

If White succeeds in keeping this "strong" pawn center he will definitely have the better game. Yet if black accomplishes his goal of undermining and / or trading off White's pawns in my opinion he will probably gain equality and if White is not careful Black can gain a strong advantage.

***********************************************************************

On the other hand in the French Defense Black willingly accepts a restricted LSB and possibly a restricted King-side. The French is fairly popular though so obviously many people agree with me that the tactical battle which ensues makes these "minor inconveniences" worthwhile.

So you chose to play the Exchange Variation: 3.exd5. Although it is sound it lacks the intense battle or complications of some of the other variations mentioned above. Exchanging pawns on d5 removes the tension that is frequently part of this defense. Therefore it is usually avoided by most advanced players. For this same reason though it's probably the best line for beginners playing White against the French Defense. Until a player learns how to make in depth calculations complications should be avoided.

An interesting note after the pawns are exchanged the pawn structure and overall position looks nothing like the French Defense although it still is the French!
3...Qxd5(?) would give White unwarranted initiative with moves like 4.Nc3 or 4.c4. It would also leave Black without a pawn presence in the center. Thus 3...exd5.
Good move developing towards the center. The knights are usually best on c3 & f3 or for Black c6 & f6. It's also good usually to bring the knights out before the bishops as you are doing.
Ditto for me.

So the reason the knights should be out first is that you usually don't know where the bishops should be placed. If your position is such that you know where they should go and you have a specific reason for bringing them out then bring them out. In this case I wanted to prevent you from pinning my king-knight with Bg5.
Since Bg5 would not be a pin I agree this is the better move. Your bishop covers more squares on f4 than g5.
The next string of moves I don't annotate because I feel you were simply making good developing moves. For my next annotation see 10.h3.

(?) You needed more protection on the DSB. After 11...Bxf3 12.Qxf3 you only have a pawn defending. You could have played 10.Re1.

***********************************************************************

So you had one piece defending the d4 pawn (White Move 8). I pinned that piece(Black Move 8) so you add extra defense to the pawn (White Move 9). So I redirect my attack to the Bishop which defends the pawn (Black Move 9). 

***********************************************************************

Now you have a pawn defending the bishop and a knight defending but the knight is pinned so not really. So you play 10.h3(?). I need to do something with the bishop since you attack him. So I use him to remove the defending knight. After your queen captures your only defense to the bishop is the pawn while I have my bishop and knight attacking him. So I exchange on the e5 square winning a pawn.
Remove the defender!

I normally prefer my bishops over knights. This is because while knights are the stronger piece in cramped closed positions bishops are stronger in open positions. So you have to consider each game individually but generally as pieces get traded off closed positions become open positions in the middle game and end game. As the position opens up the bishops become stronger and stronger. So although both pieces are technically the same value the bishops are my piece of choice. That may be just a personal thing though because while most strong chess players agree with me I've met some who disagree. So here I take your bishop with my knight instead of my bishop.

So I have won the battle of the pawns I was speaking of on your 2nd move. Your center pawns have been eliminated and one of them was taken for free. Yet I am the one who still has a pawn in the center on d5!

So my advantage is now my pawn on d5. You prepare to harass my pawn by putting your rook on the file. In addition in doing this you also brought your rook to the center to a semi open file (which would be completely open if you win that pawn). Rooks are better in the center than they are on the edge on the board. They are best on open files 2nd best on semi open files and least effective on closed files.

So I solidify his stronghold! In addition I am putting my pawns on light colored squares. This is because we have opposite color bishops; you have a LSB I have a DSB. So in putting my pawns on light squares I give my bishop more freedom and restrict your bishop. This move also opens another line of attack for my queen along the d8 a5 diagonal. At this point I am considering Qb6 to attack the Pawn on b2 or Qa5 to bolster the bishops attack on your knight. I am also considering Bc7 followed by Qd6 to attack your king.

Now you bring your other rook to a completely open file. Good for you. You now have both rooks on central squares and one of them on a an open file! The fact that I have a Bishop on that file does not mean it is semi-open. Whether a file is open semi-open or closed is determined by pawns.

***********************************************************************

In addition you are attacking my bishop so I must attend to that.

Defending the Bishop while bringing a rook to the center open file. I wanted to play Bc7 followed by Qd6. The problem with that is you are ahead in development with your 2 central rooks. My rooks are still on their original squares. I needed to develop also before I attempt to develop an attack.

15.a4(?) A valiant attempt at some queen-side action but this makes it hard to defend your b-pawn. After 15...Qb6 if you chose to defend the pawn you need to play 16.Rb1. Then I would play 16...Qb4 increasing my attack on your Knight. If you play 17.Nd1 your previously coordinated pieces become somewhat spastic. Your rooks are no longer connected and you have a knight on the back rank.

***********************************************************************

If instead you play 16.Bf4 or 16.Bf1 to defend the knight with your queen I can play 16...Bxc3 followed by Qxa4. winning a 2nd pawn.
Attack!

So you chose to give me the pawn. I was thinking you may have been planning 16...Bxb2 17.Rb1 then following up with a attack on the pinned bishop. I would have played 17...Qb4. It will take some time to get your other artillery over to the queen-side this would give me time to play Qa3 removing the pin b6 to close your attack on the b-file and then moving my bishop back. 

***********************************************************************

I would not play 16...Qxb2 as you get too much counter-play with 17.Rb1 Qa6 18.Rxb7 Qxa4 19.Reb1.
My 2nd free pawn.
Threatening 18...Rxe1 so you need to either move the rook off the open file or trade. With my material lead trading is good for me while if you move off the file you weaken your position.
And trade you did!
Again my threat 19...Re1+.
19.Rb1(!?). Of course this does nothing for you since I am about to force the trade with the rook check.
So the reason it is to my advantage to trade is that if we trade off all equal material it will leave me with a 2 pawn lead in the end game.

Now there is no way to defend the f-pawn unless you want to play 22.Bxe4. I did not have mate formulated in my mind yet so I want to win pawns to get the greatest advantage in the end-game.  

***********************************************************************

Be careful though when you go grabbing pawns that you don't leave your king or other pieces in a precarious position. Notice each time I take a pawn you have no means of retaliation.

With this move of yours I am starting to plan how to mate you. I am attempting to form a net around your king. I just spoke of how I wanted to trade and 2 moves ago I would have accepted a queen trade gladly. Yet now since I was seeing mate in the near future (though not yet worked out in detail) I did not want to trade queens. I was sure she would be helpful in the mate process. Currently your king has no squares he can move to. Yet since I plan to capture the f-pawn with my knight the king will have g3 as escape hatch. Soooo...
22...Be5+ cuts off the kings access to g3.

You sent me a message to say you should have blocked the check with 23.g6. Well that would have stopped this particular mate I would go into the end game with a 3 pawn lead. That is more than enough for a win.
Obviously you saw the mate threat 24...Qh1# (the knight is pinned) or you would not have sacked your bishop.
You are prolonging your agony! Just kidding I actually always suggest people I mentor play the games out as still there may be things I can teach.

Taking the bishop would have the same results it would just take longer. 25...Kxh7 26.Qf5+ (not 26.Qh5 Kg1 and no more checks for white) Kh6 (not 26...Kh8 or 26...Kg8 as white would have 27.Qc8+ delaying things further) and the white queen has no more checks.
Now the mate threat is (as I'm sure you know) 26....Bxg3 27.Kh1 Qf1#. It's been good Chase thanks for the game!

"Best by test." -- Bobby Fischer
I guess I'll stick to that simple and logical first move for quite the rest of my life though the Bird (1. f4) or even crazy openings like the Orangutan (1. b4!?) or the Grob attack (1. g4!?) are pretty interesting too and could be great surprise weapons at least in Blitz.

The passive but sound French defence consisting of tons of theory. The usual continuation here is the logical 2. d4 d5 when White has already at least four common choices to proceed (Main Line 3. Nc3 Advance Variation 3. e5 Tarrasch Variation 3. Nd2 Exchange Variation 3. exd5). Ignoring the logical central pawn move I was really looking forward to the rest of the game at this point because it was the first time I could use a rare Anti-French opening weapon in tournament play. It's called the...
... Reti-Gambit! Well it's not a gambit at this point as there are still all pawns alive but the usual continuation leads White to the possibility of sacrificing a pawn.
Challenging the center quite a logic move in regards of the previous 1... e6.
White ignores his attacked central pawn and just proceeds with quick development. You can see that the bishop is quite strong on this place here already eyeing g7.
Black accepts the gambit (a healthy decision however like in all gambits you have to be careful) now the fun begins!
Another development move which immediately attacks the lost pawn.
Black gets his first minor piece out and defends the won pawn.

The fight against the e4 pawn continues. This move might look odd because it blocks the bishop but a central idea in the Reti Gambit is queen-side castling for occupying the d-file and the light-squared bishop can simply be developed via g2 or h3 afterwards.
Black develops and obviously plans to kill one attacker of the e4 square to hold the gambit pawn.

In the spirit of the gambit White just continues developing. It can never hurt to place a rook on the same file than the opponent's queen ;-) Notice that winning back the pawn via 6. Nxe4?? fails due to 6... Nxe4 7. Qxe4 Qxd2 mate.

?! I was very surprised by this move and consider it as weak because it allows White to open up the d-file and gives away the pair of bishops. It's primary the opponents greed about holding this won pawn which motivates this move I guess.
Doubled pawns and the temporary blocked dark-squared bishop are the price for the mighty open d-file.
Facing the rook the queen has to move (or as an alternative get pinned) of course.
Occupying space on the king-side and preparing to develop the light-squared bishop. A later advance to g5 attacking the knight could also be useful. This was the reason I preferred g4 over g3.
The opponent already seems to fear the pawn advance because it would leave the pawn on e4 undefended.
So the second bishop is on the long diagonal as-well and the recapturing possibility of the gambit pawn is again on (though it would give away the pair of bishops).
Freeing the bishop hoping for simple tactics 10... Bxg4!

Maybe winning back the pawn with 10. Bxe4 Bxg4 11. Bf3 would even have been a sound possibility however I didn't want to corrupt my pawn structure and this way the mobility of Black's bishop is also limited.
Develops but also sets up a trap in case White takes the pawn. 11. Bxe4?? fails due to 11... Nxe4 12. Qxe4 Bc6! setting up an X-ray attack winning the rook.
"The knight wants to be developed so please take me!"

I was quite satisfied with my position at this point realizing that I'm ahead in development and Black probably won't hold the pawn. The power of the two bishops on the long diagonals will also unfold soon!
Logical Black prepares to queen-side castle too and wants to defend his pawn.
Bringing the dark-squared bishop into play again increasing the pressure on e5.
Black finally gets his king to a safe place.
Increasing the pressure on the half-open e-file. The poor pawn on e5 is attacked four times but only defended twice.

It was time to win back the pawn and unfold the power of the bishops. At this point I already saw that I could probably later corrupt Black's king-side pawn structure by taking the knight on f6 heading for an endgame advantage.
Let's simplify the situation by trading of some heavy pieces...
Due to the open position Whites pair of bishops clearly have a huge advantage over Black's minor pieces.
? One defender of the bishop is missing now which enables simple pawn-winning tactics.
! Another defender of the bishop is killed now and Black's pawn structure is corrupted as it was already planned before.
The only tactical trick I used in the game winning a single pawn. However in addition to the other advantage of the better pawn structure it is enough for an easy win.
Now White's rook is on the powerful 7th rank too (I guess 20... Kd8 would have lasted longer for that reason) already attacking a pawn Black is dead lost.
While Black is in defending mode...
... White can calmly bring his king into the action.
Being banished from the 7th rank the rook finds another nice place where it also cuts off the Black king from the action.
Intending Rg5 hoping for a resolution of the doubled pawns?

If 21... BxB 22 RxQ CHECK forces Black's hand. 22... RxR or 22... KxR is followed by 23 QxB with a winning advantage of a Q for a R and a Pawn ahead to boot.
If 24... QxB 25 RxQ secures a winning material edge. So Black tries 24 RxB...

Now I really have the advantage. Now threatening the bishop + b2.

Exchanging the pieces. White is now totally unfanged and underdevelopped. The only advantage he got right now is the pawns in the middle. Maybe to keep his bishop by returning back to c1 would have given better attack further in the game for white.

! By doing so it give me a nice passage for my rook to the king and a better position to attack. Don't forget that if I would have taken it with my queen white would have done e4-e5 giving him better counter-attack. Anyway my king is not threated at all and it will be better if I castle on the queen side.
Protecting the b pawn and preparing d4 forking my queen and my bishop + it solidify the center.
Avoiding the trap and threatening h2.
I think f4 would have been better here.
Now there's many possibilities of attack on my side! My rook is prepared so I can make Bg4 in the next moves. I'm already planning to make a x mate with my queen and my bishop on h3 and f3.
I can't take the e pawn because of Re1.
Ready to execute my plan.
Well my defense is breaking and I will probably not able to castle but I still think I have advantage.

I look in a bad situation but I really think the situation of white is worst. Anyway his rook and his knight is not developped and I would probably be able to castle before he does any threats to my king. 

From my side I'm now ready to unleash a huge attack. The f2 pawn is now pinned and there's now many way to reach the king. With the knight I've got in the beginning of the game I don't really care right now to sacrifice some of my pieces. Bxf2 or Bg4 would be a nice continuation for black.
! By doing this not only he protects the f pawn but he stops the threat of bg4 + it give him space to do Qf1 avoiding an x mate with my bishop and my queen.

Hi everyone!

This game was played between my master buddy Freddy the Master Mater and a Class C player called Concordborn (Matthew).  This game certainly belongs under the It Can Be Done thread.  OK it was a draw and not a win although in the middlegame Matthew had great winning chances being a piece ahead but alas allowed Freddy back into the game by getting his knight trapped.  Matthew did get a pawn for the knight and ended up in a same coloured bishop ending where he remained a pawn up right until the end.  However because Freddy had put his king right up into his opponent's arc Matthew had to be content with a Master Draw - at least it took him only 3 attempts to get there as opposed to my 50!  Anyhow gameknot analysis is right here:- http://gameknot.com/analyze-board.pl?bd=14233842&rnd=0.8639711164224122
4. .... Be7 - very conservative development on both sides following a double Queen Pawn Opening.
6. ..... 0-0 - Matthew tucks his king away on the kingside but is any king safe when your opponent is Freddy?!
7. ..... c4 - Matthew tries to cramp Freddy for style.
12. ...... Ne8 - Matthew had to retreat his knight here.  An interesting battle with the footmen going on in the centre - a real stonewall.
13. ..... Ng7 - Matthew's king looks a little draughty - give him some cover - do!  Matthew does but with a knight rather than a bishop.  A bishop is better for this kind of thing methinks.
16. Bh6 - would e5 have been a good move I wonder?
18. Bg5?? - this move will cost Freddy a whole piece - however will the 800 point rating differential save Freddy?  Only time will tell.
19. e5 - Freddy certainly ain't gonna topple his king here he is trying to counter-attack by going for the throat.
21. ...... Qxg5 - Matthew forces an exchange of rooks before taking off Freddy's knight.  Now if Matthew can maintain his material advantage into the endgame it will be decisive.
24. exf6 - Matthew naturally exchanges queens to do try and simplify into that won ending.  Alas the knight on g7 is trapped and if Ne8 then f7+ wins it next turn.
26. ..... Kxg7 - Matthew has simplified into an endgame a pawn up.  That should really be enough to win although Matthew's extra pawn on e6 is backward so it may make things rather difficult there.
28. .... Bc8 - hmm rather passive but it is difficult to find the right plan here.
30. hxg5 - pawn trade.
32. Kf4 - Freddy's king advances up the board and is threatening to infiltrate via e5/d6.
33. .... Ke7 - but Matthew's king prevents this.

35. .... Bc6 and DRAW OFFER - Freddy accepts the draw offer as there is no way through the gate - Freddy has been stonewalled and must now concede a Low Draw although for him it could have been far far worse.  Anyhow hope you all have a good read and you Walk the Walkers take heart from this - it is possible to achieve something other than a big fat zero against The Master Mater!
On a blitz game I won't think too much: the Reti is an "open" start move I just will go to the scheme I know best.
I already know I would play h6 e6 c5 almost for sure.
White helped me with this passive opening.

But now something changes. This is the first "real" move. Ok no problem. I will retreat my bishop and the naughty knight can go nowhere to be dangerous while it is ready to be kicked away with c5 - or even e5 if I decide so.

Ok the good thing is this way I will get some tempo sooner or later attacking h2. The bad part is that he will be able to press hard on the diagonal - and b7 if ever my pawn chain gets open. Which is not likely just now but wait...

Normal he wants to put a question mark on my pawn chain. Now d4 is the "normal" move. He can exchange the pawns or the bishop but nothing too dangerous. So I tried something more interesting... at a blitz sight.

Now I am the one that threats the white diagonal and the nasty knight is mine. Look: incredibly enough it is not that easy for him to defend d3! It just lacks of a minor piece behind it! Let's see what he does.
He went for it. A logic decision for a blitz game. Now again I can play Nxd5 (or exd5) etc. etc. But I went for the tactic.

A lot of things are possible here. If dxe6 the white bishop can take b7 threatening my rook and e6 can take f7 giving check and weakening my king's position. On the other side my bishop is threatening the rook f1 and the knight is approaching to a fork on c2. Normally those forks are bad because I will lose two pieces for a rook. BUT I had the feeling (I couldn't calculate it) that the knight will survive: look after he takes the rook e1 (it will be there if he tries to save it) the queen would have taken the bishop and I will be able to play NxBf3 with check so no danger...

He did the first part. I would have played dxe6 leaving me the decision to be greedy (BxRf1) or try to save the day with fxe6. This one is bad since white throws in Bh5+ and my king goes dangerously out in the worst possible way no matter BxR or Nc2 winning another rook I will probably be lost. But he behaves... good boy!

I still have Nc2 but I didn't want to give away the B unless necessary. This way I prevent some bad surprise on the diagonal ensuring a retreat point for my bishop etc. I think I could have though about c4 solidifying the bishop and making Nc2 much more dangerous but I was not sure about e6xf7+...
Ok so he makes it so I have to prove my early intuition was right. Here I go:
Yes the only flaw in the plan. But too bad and too late. Anyway I have won the exchange I only have to keep the knight and don't lose it.

Long story: My Queen is stuck between two guarded knights (one is pinned to the King) and can't move unless I really wanted to lose the game entirely. Here Black could have been a bit more aggressive with Bc5.

White chooses to defend e4 with the Rook (instead of Nc3) to occupy the e-file and to build a strong center with c3-d4-Nd2.
Black should have acted against White's plans by either Re8 or d6.

White strangely does not take the Nc3 which is normal in the Ruy-Lopez: moreover Black has casted already so the Bb5 is not threatening the fork in case Black plays d6 or d5.
Alternative variation: 7.Bxc6 [Better would have been to take the Nc3 the only defender of e5.] 7...bxc6 [Take with b7 instead of d7 to open the b-file for the R and to allow d5 later.] 8.Nxe5 Rb8
Black seems better developed so he tries to free up the game crushing White's center.
White tries to close the game maybe to prepare an attack on the King-side. But he's still underdeveloped and most of his pieces are on the Queen-side.
Make some space for Na5 and shift some power on the King-side just in case.
Characteristic move of the Ruy-Lopez to prepare an attack on the King-side.
The N seems more effective in e3 or g3 bulding up some pressure on f5.
This is a loss of time. Action is on the King-side and Black should continue with the idea started with f7-5 either by f4 or fxe4.
With this move White shows his intention to move Rg1 in order to continue his attack. Therefore Black should take advantange of that and take fxe4.

Black should have taken fxe4.
Alternative variation: 17...fxe4 18.Rxe4 c4 =+ [And Black's Knights have two beautiful squares to occupy: c5 and f6.]
To put some pressure on the Queen-side but there seems to be enough already. Better would be Nf6.

Now Black has two powerful passed pawns backed up by his Rooks.
White tries an attack on the King-side in order to shift the attention from his falling Queen-side.
White does not seem to have enough power to break through Black's King-side.

White's Rook is hanging and Black should take advantage of it. Instead with fear he defends g7 (and attack Rg5) but without taking the initiative.

This weakens the already weak g2 and it fails to threaten Rh5 because of the next-to-come fork Rg1.
Make some room for the Queen to get to g2.

White aims to simplify the game but this move clears the board of many pieces and the two Black's passed pawns increase their value.
Alternative variation: 36.Ng4 a2 37.Nxe5 a1=Q 38.Rxa1 Rxa1+ 39.Bxa1 +/- [And Black's position look really bad with his King completely exposed.]
Black should lose no time and push his pawn a3.
Again a weak move from Black. Better would be Nh5.
Black fails to see Rh8+ but just for few moves. Time is running out.
White was already busted but this move is the definitive mistake.
A rather tame opening variation by my opponent not putting pressure on me at once as White can do with certain choices of opening.
I naturally don't want to let White plant his Knight on a powerful central outpost hence the exchange.

I cut off the attack on KB2 at once.
Mow that White's KB is off the board I can afford to try and generate my own attack on his K-side where I assume he will place his King.
Focusing on *White's* KB2.

I refocus on White's KB2...

Pinning...

Moving my second Rook into position.

..about this move.

This game is one I thought I played fairly well. It is good to have luck on your side also. Kings Opening. I am especially weak playing as black. Partially because the guy that got me into playing chess always let me start the games as white. I played probably 300 games as white before I ever played a game as black. Feel free to comment or point out a move I missed or even how lucky I was this game.
Evans Gambit accepted. All move up to this point are text book moves.
Ulvestad variation. Still all fairly text book moves. But we are close to getting this game rolling.
Paulsen variation. Now we roll right into the game play.
I thought I would go ahead and come out of the gate a little aggresive. I knew I had to jump on gcah2006 to many times allowing the better player to be aggresive I get into trouble fairly quickly.
This move stops 13. h3. Which would be followed by blacks 13. Bxh3 and opening up the h & g files for a direct attack on the King.

It worked. I feel this move helped me gain a tempo (maybe not I'm faily new to this game).

An exchange I have to do to get my queen involved in the attack.
This move is the one that sealed the deal. I think gxf3 would have been the better move.

The most common response

I think this is a strange move I have never seen it before.  I have seen 4 Nc3. If 4 dxe5 black plays Nxe4 with and aprox equal position

Reducing the tension in the centre but now we will see that the g5-bishop is not very well placed
Now I do not like this move I could have played Be7 letting the c5-square for the knight in the future (after c6 Qc7)
Developping the N to d2 with the idea of covering the d4-square with c3 in the future
Gaining space in the Q-side. I had to try something in the K-side but with my B on c5 that is dificult (because I have to do Nc5-e6)

Qb3!? trying to defend the b4-pawn for ezample 13 Qb3 a5 14 a3 and white is ready to play c4
White was threatening c4

20 Nxe5?! Nxg3! 21 Nxd7 Nxe2+ 22 Kh1 Rxd7 and Black is slightly better with three pieces against a queen
20 Bxe5 Nxe5 21 Nxe5 Qxd2 22 Qxd2 Rxd2 23 Bxh5 g6 24 Bf3 Bf6 and bxc4 with some winning probabilities
Now in this position no one has real winning posibilities. We followed playing only by inertia
Grand Prix Attack.  A good aggressive line to play against the Sicilian though it does tend to telegraph the punches just a little bit...
This is usually why you don't see the Grand Prix all that much.  But White's game is still quite playable.
Invites Black's reply.  White has a certain gambit in mind...

Inviting ...Nf6 to protect the lead e-pawn.  White is aiming for a line I have dubbed the 'Demolition Derby' Attack:  4...Nf6  5.Bc4!? (apparently allowing Black to win White's Queen) ...Bg4  6.Bxf7ch Kd7  7.Qxg4 Nxg4  8.Be6ch ... 9.Bxg4.  For the Queen White gets active play and Black has difficulty just developing.  The jury is still out on the soundness of this ultra-violent line.  (I wonder if  'A Clockwork Orange' Attack wouldn't be a better appellation?  Maybe that should go with the Caro Kann version...).
Black is having none of it.  Jo has built up a fund of experience with the 4...Nf6 line which may be why Charles gave it the go-by.
(!?) I have my doubts about this though I won't condemn it out of hand.  It seems to me 5.Bc4 was still a good move here.
The obvious response.  Yet there was something to be said for 5....Nc6 even though Black might have got a lot of doubled pawns scattered about: 5...Nc6  6.Bxc6 bxc6  7.Nxe4 exf4 ...

In effect White has gambited a pawn but doesn't have all that much for it.  Could this be one of those positional gambits the hypermoderns used to play with a view to the ending?  White has the Q-side majority (which proves to be a major motif in this game) but realising it seems a long way off.

Pragmatic: continuing her development.  But worth considering was 8.Qe2 a move that has some developmental value but tests Black's alertness.  If he were to play say 8...Nf6 then 9.Nd6# ends proceedings right there.  Black would just about have to play his lone already-developed piece (8...Ne4) to remain on roughly level terms.
Rather awkward as it interferes with the development of the other knight.  Too bad: there doesn't seem to be anything better.

An interesting development.  Black wants to maintain that lead f-pawn for as long as possible.  Was he already contemplating a direct attack upon White's King?  Note that the bishop exerts through the f-pawn a certain amount of pressure on h2.

(!?)  Sticking to his plan of attack against h2 and maintains the lead f-pawn for the time being as well.  The GK engine mislikes this in favour of 10...Ne2  11.Nb5!? Be5  12... 0-0-0.  This alternative is less committal but equally less forcing.  The game continuation does however give White the opportunity for counter-action.

(!?) Thematic but the GK engine indicates 11.Nb5 ought to have come first with attack against d6 and c7.  After 11.Nb5 the engine suggests 11...Bb8  12.Qf3 with threats against f4 and b7.  But 11...Be5 seems better as after 12.Qf3 Ne7  13.Qxb7?? Rb8  14.Qa6 Rb6  looks very nasty.  Instead 13.Bxf4 keeps things more or less level.  My own view is that the text move is unobjectionable.

Further protection for f4 and stormclouds appear to be gathering darkly on the King-side.  Though 11...0-0-0 was more solid White would have been able by 12.Bxf4 somewhat to blunt Black's attack.  As it happens White doesn't appear to be much fazed by Black's threatening attitude...
Wins back the pawn and leaves Black centre and Q-side looking very porous.

(!?) Sensible-looking and centralising yet the GK engine doesn't approve.  According to its wisdom 13.Qa6 ought to have been played.  I'm inclined to agree as that move combines attack on a7 as well as d6.  But I think White wanted to keep the Queen nearer the action bearing in mind her Q-side has yet to make a move.
(!) Good defence: keeps a watch over f4 (and h2) and closes off the e-file (else White might have continued Qe6ch and Re1).

As planned I suspect but White might equally well have considered beginning to bring out her Q-side: 14.Nd2 with 15.Nf3 to follow.  Black has a bit of a lead in development that White can not afford to see become much longer.

Black has to forgo castling as after 14...Ne7  15.Nd5! g4  16.Bxf4 Bxf4  17.Rxf4 Kd8 and white can exchange down into a very promising endgame: 18.Qxe7ch Qxe7  19.Nxe7 Kxe7  20.b3 - White would have the stronger pawns and an extra pawn as well.
(!?) Once more GK prefers 15.Nd2.  But White has it in mind to stymie once and for all Black's K-side offensive.
Forcing the exchange but in fact White had no choice here.  Black's ...Ng4 threat had to be answered at once.  Now the Queens come off.
An intermezzo.  Black uses the check to improve the placing of the bishop.

According to the GK analysis Black's (slight) edge was slowly dissipating.  This can be a problem when gambiting material which in effect Black has done in recent moves and is now a pawn behind.  That the Queens are disappearing won't be altogether welcome in that context.  Once the compensating intangibles (time space initiative) disappear which they tend to do given time then the material advantage will come into its own.
Discouraging the knight's development to d2?

Apparently so.  Interestingly GK suddenly gives a noticeable plus in favour of Black at this point but without giving any reason why or noting any improvement White might have.  19.Nd2? Ne3 could not be countenanced but how about 19.Ne4 preparing the way for the other knight?  An interesting forcing line ensues: 19.Ne4!? Ne3  20.Bxe3 Bxb2  21.Bd2 Bxa1  22.Ng5 with a complicated endgame to look forward to.  That White will have given up the exchange offers an intriguing counterpoint to the actual game.
(!?) Inhibiting the a3-Knight's further progress.  Also playable here was ...Bxc3 breaking up White's pawns.
To free up the bishop.  White is steadily catching up in development.  However 20.h4 was worth looking at to disrupt Black's K-side (though Black would probably have responded ...h6).

At last all White's pieces are in action though Black's are still appreciably the more dynamic right now.  But there's the distinct feel to the game that suggests White is gradually beginning to assert her own stamp on proceedings.  If Black wants to make progress he'll have to do something - and that pretty shortly.

(!?) Aron Nimzovitch used to write about the 'mysterious rook move'.  Well the motivation for this move is pretty obscure unless Black was planning on a switch to the a-file or maybe to the K-side.  Or did Charles have some nefarious other scheme in mind?  We'll come to that...
A pawn ahead White wants piece exchanges provided she doesn't have to make concessions to bring them about.  All the same 22.h4 was still worth considering.

This pawn phalanx is Black's strike force and will always constitute a danger White has to watch.  White's majority on the other wing will take much longer to mobilise.  All the same the GK engine rated the position as dead level at this point.  I'm inclined to agree.

(?/?!)  The first real mistake of the game according to GK.  A straightforward oversight it must have seemed to Jo when she saw this position.  But you know I am beginning to wonder about that.  Could Black have seen that his advantages were gradually eroding away and something needed to be done to create a wider range of possibilities even at the risk of conceding to his opponent real winning chances?  Maybe Charles can answer that question...
Correct.  There's nothing against taking the proffered material and everything to recommend it.

Now is the time to assess the situation.  White is the rough equivalent of a piece ahead: Rook and pawn for a Knight.  But the extra pawn is doubled and a Rook's pawn at that.   Further Black's pieces are all nicely centralised with plenty of collaborative potential.  White's for the moment remain scattered.  And there is that niggling problem of the Black K-side majority well advanced and ready to go if given the chance.  I'm not saying Black has enough to hold on even for a draw; but he's got plenty to have a good old crack at it and even maybe turn the tables.  White has to tread very carefully and yet play decisively enough not to let slip her own chances to win.  Game on!
Not a bad start: offer a piece exchange.  After 27..Bxf2 28.Kxf2 White will have conceded nothing to rid herself of Black's most mobile piece.
So: no sale.

(?!)  Offering another exchange but this does concede something and more in my view than White ought to have been prepared to yield.  GK agrees preferring 28.b4.  Now the line GK follows is certainly very attractive for White: 28.b4 cxb4!?  29.Rxb4 Bc3  30.Rb1 Bd2(!?)  31.Bxb6 Nxb6  32.Rxb6 Be3.  At this point GK gives 33.Rb8 but I would probably play instead 33.Rxd6ch Kxd6  34.Nc4ch Kc5  35.Nxe3 fxe3  36.Kf3 Kd4  37.a4.  Even at the cost of giving up the exchange this simplification brings us down to a winning pawn ending.  If Black tries 28...Bd4 then 29.bxc5 brings about the mobilisation of White's own pawn majority.

Writes down part of White's material advantage and with this pawn doubled the White majority will be a little harder to get going.  While I'm at it many beginners and probably intermediate players too find minor pieces difficult to use without the aid of the heavy pieces.  This game offers a fine example of how they might be handled even in a difficult defence.  Be it noted though: White still has a considerable probably winning edge here.
Really I don't like this move but it can't be helped.  The lead c-pawn requires protection.
Black has seized the initiative - for the moment at least - to make progress on the K-side.   But White seems well placed in defence on that wing.
Well: White's h-pawn has been 'undoubled' for what that might be worth...  That means that there are fewer obstacles in frnt of Black's K-side pawns.

I can't find any improvement for either side in the last 5 moves.  Black's K-side has made some progress but seems to be stymied for now.  White now conjures up a threat of her own to mobilise her Q-side.  Once those pawns break loose. it will be all up for Black.
Hence this retreat to keep the rook out of d6.

(?!) I believe that Jo had already worked out a plan to mobilise the Q-side in which this pawn was to advance to a5 backed up by the bishop on the e1-a5 diagonal.  I'll come back to that.  But I really dislike this move as making it harder to unleash the pawns.  Preferable is 34.a3 with the b4 advance in mind.  One possible line is 34.a3 Nc6 (say)  35.Rd5ch Be5  36.h4! f3ch  37.Kf1 Bf4  38.h5 g3  39.Bxg3 Bxg3  40.h6 and ironically White's K-side pawn wins the day!

Black has certainly the upper hand on the dark squares.  But it's hard to see how even this will prevail in the long run given White has the means to contest Black's dark-square ascendancy: her bishop.

(?!) Here is Jo's plan: to shove forward the Q-side pawns with the bishop's backing.  The c-pawn will be undermined and the rook will take it out.  Well thought out but and this was sheer bad luck it turns out to be a mistaken plan.  By committing herself to the Q-side White allows Black some slack on the other wing.  There were good alternatives in 35.Rd5; 35.Bg1 (I like this move); or even in waiting 35.Kf1.  However This is not the losing move - in fact I reckon White still had the winning of the game after this move but this was one of those rare situations in which following a plan proves ones undoing.

(?) With this move probably White's winning chances start to fade away.  The GK engine prefers 36.Rd2 here though with ...Bg5 and ...f3ch in the air it is easy to pass this move by.  After 36.Rd2 Bg5  37.Kf1 Ke5  38.Bf2 f3  39.Bxd4ch cxd4  40.Rd3 Ke4  41.Rd1 Bf4   42.Kg1 Bg5  43.b4 Bh4  44.Kf1 and Black's K-side attack is running out of steam whilst White's pawns are ready to roll.  A whole different plan which seems less to teeter on the edge of the abyss was 36.c3! with the idea 36...Nxb3 37.Rb1 Na5 38.Rxb6ch Ke7  39.Rb5 Nxc4  40.Rxc5.

The GK engine still gives White an edge but already this is looking doubtful.  Though still nominally a piece down Black still has that menacing K-side and the more active pieces and pawns.  White's game is looking harder to get rolling than even a couple of moves ago...
According to plan.  More complicated was 37.b4 but it might have been worth a look.

The complicating factor is the threatened fork at e3 which persists after White's next.  All the same GK now considered the game evenly balanced.  This would have been a disappointment to Jo but immersed as she was in her scheme to break the chains about her Q-side pawns no doubt thought she still had the better of it and soon she would be home free.

(?) Twin passers on the Q-side!  The culmination of White's plan... and the move that put even the draw out of reach.  It just one of those horrible situations in which you suddenly realise that the creaking of the thin ice that you thought was coming from under the other guy's feet were actually being caused by your own bootsteps.  Who said it?  'Chess is a cruel game...'  Better chances of a draw were offered in these lines: [a] 40.Rd7  f3ch  41.Kf1 Bd4  42.Bd2 Kd3  43.Bg5 Na1  44.Rf7 Nxb3   45.h3  Be3  46.Rd7ch Bd4  47.Rf7 with a repetition; or [b] 40.Bd2 f3ch  43.Kf1 Be5   44.Rxc5 Bxh2  45.Rg5 g3  46.Rg4ch Kd3  47.Bf4 g2ch (...Ne3ch=) 48.Kf2 g1=Qch  49.Rxg1 Bxg1ch  50.Kxg1 =.

(?) But 41.Kh1 still lost after 41...f2  42.Kg2 Bh4  43.Re5ch! - The best White can do to slow things down was to give up the rook for nothing - 43...Kxe5.  Mind you White could still have resisted for a while even brought about a close finish:  44.Bb6 Ne1ch  45.Kf1 Nf3  46.Bxf2! Nxh2ch!  47.Kg2 Bxf2  48.Kxf2 Kf4  49.b4  {or 49.c5 Nf3  50.c6 Nd2!  51.c7 Ne4ch  52.Kg2 Nd6  53.b4 Nc8 etc} 49...Nf3  50.b5 g3ch  51.Kg2 Nh4ch  52.Kg1 Nf5  53.c5 Ne7  54.c6 Ne8 etc.  Interesting also would have been 41.Kg3 Bh4ch!  42.Kxh4 f2  43.Bc7 f1=Q  44.Re5ch Kd3 but White's pawns are too scattered and weak for her to set up any kind of fortress.

(0-1) At this point Jo tossed in the sponge: there's no cure for ...f2ch.  There's a good deal to be got out of this game.  For one thing it shows how hard it can be to overcome a determined defence.  In this game for all his material deficit Black had a good deal to play with so White's task to win the game was no light matter.  It was her truly evil luck to hit on a plan of attack that seemed to promise a clear path to her goal - her Celestial City -  only to discover it was the road into the Slough of Despond.   Ask Christian: some days you just can't win.

White is much better now. He has the opportunity to attack with Nd5 c3 or a3 with b4 and opening the position of the king. The 2 rooks can be transfered quickly. Most stronger players on this site could recieve a winning ad from this position as white. Once black hass castled a critical principle comes in play. When 2 players are castled opposite the one that gets to the other first will usually recieve the advantage. Whether it is with pieces(open positions generally) or pawns morelikely this principle will likely decide the game in these kind of positions. Black cannot really attack now he is not developed enough and his attack is hard to generate.

Sicilian defence.
Dragon variation. The idea of Black is to control black squares and attack Nd4.
White defends his Nd4.
Preventing Black's Nf3 to come to g4.
The Queen works well on the c1-h6 diagonal with Be3 attacking possibly weak Black's squares.
A tipical idea of the Sicilian defense by Black is to advance pawns on the Queen side maybe Bc8 on the a8-h1 diagonal and Ra8 to the c-file.
White develops his white bishop to a more active square but he'll need to guard it from possible advances of the Black b pawn.
According to the plan Black develops his rook on the semi-open c-file.
Bishop to safety guarding the possibly weak c2 pawn.

Better would be for Black to chase Bb3 with Na5 or control the center with Ne5 with the idea of jumping to c4. Alternatively a5 would start the pawn rolling. Black here is not following the spirit of the Sicilian Defence.
Putting pressure on Nf6. White wants to get rid of Black's Bg7.
Before recapturing the knight White takes exchanges the black bishops. Black King recaptures and he's in a dangerous square.
White can recapture with Queen or with bishop to avoid having to back up in case Black chases her. White has to be careful in case of b5 and a4 because with e6 the bishop would be trapped.
Ties White's Queen to the defence of c2.
All by the book. White starts the pawn advance on the King's side.
Black pushes but the a-pawn is not supported well enough.
White is scared by the a-pawn but it shouldn't be. He should concentrate on his King-side advance.

Black wants to stop White advance but much better would be h5 or h6 or e6. f5 leaves too many weak squares behind like: e7 (weak pawn) e6 and the whole a1-h8 diagonal where White Queen can always check on d4.
White decides to take the pawn but probably better would be h5. Maybe we wants to avoid an isolated e-pawn in case of exchange on e4.
Adding pressure to c2.
The threat of h5 is always present to Black thinks to stop it advancing to h5. White's can use his pawn majority and attack h5 anyway.

White misses the opportunity to take the a4 pawn with Qd4.
Alternative variation: 20.g4! [Better would be to continue the attack on h5.] 20...hxg4 21.fxg4 Bd7 [Bishop has to retreat to d7 and then h5 is unstoppable.]
A move that should have been done before that now has little meaning.
White has multiple targets. h5 as usual or the weak pawn on e7 with Rhe1. He chooses to carry on with h5.
Black decides to defende himself attacking White Queen-side. But it's not a good idea.
White's King-side pawns are wrecked and now White's Queen need to guard f3 too.
Correctly White wants to exchange Queens and go in an endgame with the advantage.
Black's idea is to push d and e pawns with support by his King.
g5 is doubly attacked so Black advances it where it is guarded by both K and R.
Better would have been to ignore the pawn with Kg4 and push the d-pawn more.
At this point either the a4 pawn or the e7 pawn are doomed by either Rh4 or Re5 (if Ke3). Black chooses to save his e-pawn.
The two passed pawns are too powerful and even if White has a bishop this match will end in a draw.

Hi everyone!

So I see you enjoyed that game where I gave my Class C opponent a hard time with a central pawn push.  In this game (which began with a Queen Pawn Opening) against a Class A 1800+ opponent it was one passer on one side and two connected pawns on the other in a rook and pawn ending.  Although the connected pawns were on the kingside they were not passed.  However my decoy pawn enticed the rooks to be swapped off and my kingside pawn majority proved decisive.  Glenda's arrival heralded victory for Yours Truly.  Gameknot Analysis is provided here: http://gameknot.com/analyze-board.pl?bd=16196577&rnd=0.8325142630569565
2. ..... dxc4 - with this move a Queen's Gambit Accepted.

12. ...... Ncb4 - trying to improve the position of my knights.
14. Qg4 - ssss here comes the Wicked Witch of the West and she is bearing down on Henry!
15. Qg3 - the Witch Ejection Plan only partially works as she still stays on that g file and while she stays there there is the possibility of Bh6 putting Henry in Old Matey's Shadow.
16. ..... Ne8 - my knight retreats to a poor square to ensure that Henry does not cop Old Matey on g7.
17. ..... bxc6 - pawn trade.
19. Be5 - renewing the pressure on g7.
21. ..... exd5 - pawn trade.
24. dxe5 - bishop trade.
24. .... Rb8 - it looks as if I am gonna drop my c6 pawn here.  I must therefore rustle up some counterplay pronto.  Firstly I pile up on white's lsb on b3.
25. ..... qb4 - Glenda puts the a5 pawn under the hammer.
27. Bxd5 - so I lose a pawn after all but I am in no mood to throw in the sponge.  Time to shake off this passivitis - Joanne and get a few threats in to keep your opponent busy at the least!
29. ..... Kh8 - I think I will regain my pawn deficit but Henry is forced onto h8 and is therefore more susceptible to catching Old Matey on the back row.
30. .... Rxa4 - after white decided to give his own king some luft I decided to regain my pawn.  I now have a passer on a4.
32. ..... Rxh4 - pawn grab hope I do not regret it only time will tell.

33. .... Qh6! - I was soo tempted to play RxB here but I was worried about Henry on the back row.  Now incredibly it is white's king's turn to feel icy cold and see a dark dark shadow directly overhead.  It looks as though if he plays f4 to avoid copping Old Matey on h1 he will lose his rook on c1 to RxR+ RxR QxR.  But white keeps the deficit down to a mere two pawns.
36. ..... Rxc1 - although this does not now result in the win of a rook I can now simplify down to a rook ending two pawns up.  This will prove decisive in my favour never fear!

39. Ke3 - although it is Henry's turn to shiver on h8 white has no time to send Old Matey down to c8 because his king is in check.  However now that the WK has moved out of it my rook must go back to f8 to prevent this calamity.

40. .... Kg8 - Henry decided to get the Old Matey monkey off his back by moving towards the centre.  Incredibly Henry will stay rooted to this square for the rest of the game and merely watch procedings on both sides of the board.
41. Rc7 - to keep Henry pinned to the back row.
44. Ka2 - the WK blockades my passer on a3 but where there's a will there's a way!
47. Kxa3 - I am not too upset at the fact that my a pawn has dropped because the rooks are off the board and my kingside pawn majority will prove decisive as you will now see.
49. Kc3 - the WK tries to stop the black pawns from reaching Glendadom but it will be to no avail.
51. ..... gxh3 - under a set of conditional moves a decisive pawn trade takes place.  Only one dear little pawn is left on the board so why should white resign two moves down the line?

53. ..... h1/Q - well you see on h1 there is now a big black queen her name is Glenda and she is loaded with 9 units of checkmate!  So that is why white waves that white flag!  As both Henry and Glenda have shared an intimate dinner for two of garlic prawn vindaloo to celebrate their tearful reunion her breath and tongue will smell and taste particularly unpleasant to the WK so I do not blame Etienne for trying to avoid this.  Now how will she force mate from here?  Well here is a sample line.

Hi everyone!

I feel I need to give myself a bit of a lift after losing a game to an Expert that I should have won albeit I lost because I adopted the wrong plan in the endgame.  Many thanks to Coach Ion btw for annotating that game.  At least I can take some heart that I learned a lesson from GM Cyrano (annotated game here http://gameknot.com/annotation.pl/cyrano?gm=38055) about the value of connected passed central pawns.  In this game I did manage to get one of those pawns one square away from Glendadom before my opponent waved the white flag on the grounds of ruinous loss of material.  Gameknot analysis is provided here. http://gameknot.com/analyze-board.pl?bd=16118149&fb=1&rnd=0.00941152281071661
1. .... d5 - a double QP opening.
2. ..... c5 - a temporary pawn sac because if PxP then the pawn on c5 may be very difficult to retain.
5. .... Glenda emerges and hits at the b2 pawn.
7. ...... Qxc3 - in the enemy camp Glenda feasts away on another juicy p(r)awn.
11. gxf3 - I decided to trade Fou Leblanc for white's knight because I am two pawns up and so I take advantage of the pin on the d2 knight to mess up white's pawn structure on the kingside.
12. ..... fxe5 - another pawn trade gives me a strong central pawn line up.
13. ...... Bd6 - I have badly neglected my kingside development - it is time to remedy that with Fou Lenoir coming out to support that pawn centre.
14. ..... Nge7 - white regains one of his pawns and I develop my king knight to clear the decks and to block off the WR's control on my second rank.
17. ..... Nxa5 - I retain my 1 pawn advantage and I have swapped off two sets of major pieces in the process in order to get a won endgame.

18. ......Kf7 - I do not mind this check as Henry clears the way for my rook to come to wherever he pleases on the first rank.  Henry is also better nearer the centre with the queens off so I do not mind foregoing castling rights here.
22. ..... exf4 - now you have it two connected passed pawns on the c and d columns!
22. ...... Rb2 - now I return the compliment of my opponent - sticking a rook on his 2nd rank!
24. ....... Nac6 - improving the position of my knight.
26. ...... Bb4 - evading capture and putting pressure on white's position and aiding the possible further advance of those centre pawns.
28. ...... d3 - I now push on.
29. ...... d2 ...... further and now my d pawn is just one square away from Glendadom.
30. ...... c3 - and now comes his brother-in-arms.
32. Bxd4 - B for N trade.
33. Bxa7 - material is even but not for long!
33. .... c2 - fork and another footman is one step away from Glendadom.  This time white must give up his bishop to prevent this.

35. ..... Rc1+ - the killer - there is no way white can prevent Glenda from making her appearance next turn so white waves the white flag - nice win.  Hope you've all had a good read.  I will have another annotation coming up with a victory by pawn promotion this time it will be against a Class A player!  So watch this space!  Bye for now - Joanne

Here is another OTB game of mine. This is the third round of an 11 round championship but the first round where my opponent actually turned up! 
I like to start with Nf3 because of its flexibilty. I have been trying the Reti opening and Kings Indian Attack for the most part adjusting depending on what black plays.
Going for the centre and looking to set up some form of KIA.
Nothing too out of the ordinary yet.
I thought this move was a bit dubious. I'm not sure what Black's ideas were. Maybe preventing the queen from being blocked in after Nge7. Perhaps looking at Bg4 then Nd4?

Deviating from my usual KIA setup where the knight goes to d2. On this occaision there look to be potential opportunities for a knight at b5 and d5. I almost always prefer to advance the c-pawn before planting a knight here but this knight won't be there very long.
Threatening the fork at c7 and preparing for d4. Black must now castle or retreat his queen to protect the a8 rook.

Although I had already planned for d4 Black's castling gives it more potency because now the black queen and rook are on the same diagonal of the bishop I am about to release. d4 is now a double attack of sorts. Bg5 wins rook for bishop there is also a nasty little pawn fork d5.
I hadn't expected this but although interesting I think it is not one of the better moves black could have made.
Aiming at the rook on d8 whilst removing a guard from e5.
Forced

9...Qxe4+ looks an interesting response to this move but after 10 Qe2 black must either allow the white bishop to escape or exchange queens which may not be the best plan when behind in material and with a somewhat shaky position.
Not wanting to recover with the knight as it is busy where it is (overworked in fact) defending both a7 and e5.
Attacking the black queen and also discovering some protection from Qe4+ (10...dxe4 is not dangerous as it allows 11 d5)
More or less forced - the black queen only had one square to move to where it could have a chance to see move 12.
Trying to provide some protection for the d-pawn and trying to chase the knight away.
Counterattacking with threat of a nasty double-check. If 12...cxd5 13 Bxd5 Bxd5 14 Qxd5+ and Black is all but finished.
Pinning the bishop.
Gobbling up a pawn and threatening Nxc6+ or Bxc6.
Breaking the pin.
Aiming at a5 and also making way for a rook to join in the attack.
Drawing the Black king away from his defenses.
Black pins his own pawn. Nb5 threatening Qa7 or Qc7 crossed my mind but it just looked like harrassment without actually threatening anything decisive.
Bringing some more artillery into the fray.
With a rook on the d file the threat of Qc7 is far more dangerous.
The knight will fall but a rook planted on d7 (not to mention the bishop that used to be there) is more than enough compensation.
I think there are better moves than this but I saw a tactical shot that I couldn't resist...
The black queen cannot be protected.
Although it was decisive here Black fights to the bitter end.
I hope you enjoyed the annotation. Thanks for reading all comments/feedback are welcome and appreciated.
The Taminov Sicilian.
This is one of the lines where i sacrifice my queen for 3 pieces.
Forced note that if 11...Kf8 12.Nxa8 Qxa8 13.Qd6+! followed by 14.Qa3 and 15.b4 will snare my bishop. I'm not so sure about 11...Ke7 though if anyone has analysis that would be great.
Another line is 13.Qg4.
I'm not sure what to do here does anyone have a possible plan?
My position is getting uglier and uglier by the minute. I'm pretty sure i could of improved somewhere along the line but i'm not sure where.
Going for a possible 20...d5.
Where else? It's ugly but its almost forced as 20...Bd7 gets obliterated after 21.Qc4.

I couldn't find a good plan besides trying to get the knight to that newly created hole on d4 via f8 and e6 and trying to get my a7 knight back into play with Nb8 planning Nac6. I didn't like the looks of 21...Nxb5 because it gives up the A file.
At this point i think my opponent doesn't have a plan.
Encouraging 26.fxe5 because after i take with the D pawn i get the D file.
? This move drops a pawn.
Here i thought he had to take with the rook and then i had Nc2 but it doesn't really matter now.
Intresting he sacrifices a rook for a (bad) bishop and a pawn.
? Mistake on my part! I thought that after Qg8 i had Bc4 but i forgot that it was hanging. I think Nxb5 is better.
Might as well get some pawns!
Material is even now but e4 is falling and possibly f5 will too.
The bishop is very strong here as it guards f7 and b7 and still keeps a eye on g2. Also when my king gets off the seventh rank it will almost be impossible to advance his passed pawns.
Blockading the pawn.
Useless move but it is quite hard to find a plan here.
Getting the f6 pawn.
The best move to try for a win.
Haha my king is in the center but he can't mate me!
Attacking the pawn but Rg7 might be better.
Not 46...Rxb4?? as white has Qe1+!
My king is taking a nice stroll now on white territory...
Not 48.Qg1+ as 48...Ke2 wins on the spot.
White will run out of checks soon...
No checks!
Probably not the best. White cannot save a pawn here e.g. 51.g3 Nf3+ 52.Kh3 Be6+ 53.Kg2 Nxh4+ but i think giving up the H pawn is better then giving up the G pawn.
I could not find a continuation for 51...Rxg2+ after 52.Kh3. Also this threatens mate with the nice Nf3#
Stopping the threatened Nf3# and threatening Qh6 which i almost fell for.
Stopping Qxh7 (not that it matters too much) and trying to weave a mating net around white's entrapped king.
Blunder but white was pretty much lost anyway.
Blocking the check and threatening mate on h4!
Winning as 58.Kh1 is met by 58...Rg7+.
Completing the mating net. White faces mate or the loss of his queen.
